Eyes absent represents a class of protein tyrosine phosphatases. Nature 426, 295-298 (2003).
HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_caption: Eyes absent is the prototype for a class of protein tyrosine phosphatases that use a nucleophilic aspartic acid in a metal-dependent reaction; the phosphatase activity of Eyes absent contributes to its ability to induce eye formation in Drosophila

HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_description: The transcription factor Eyes absent is a protein tyrosine phosphatase. Nature 426, 299-302 (2003).
HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_caption: Experiments performed in cultured Drosophila cells and in vitro indicate that Eyes absent has intrinsic protein tyrosine phosphatase activity and can autocatalytically dephosphorylate itself

HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_description: Dach1, a vertebrate homologue of Drosophila dachshund, is expressed in the developing eye and ear of both chick and mouse and is regulated independently of Pax and Eya genes. Mech Dev 111, 75-87 (2002).
HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_caption: Eya1 IS required for normal ear develoPMENT

HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_description: A family affected by branchio-oto syndrome with EYA1 mutations. Auris Nasus Larynx 28, S7-11 (2001).
HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_caption: Mutations in the EYA1 gene have been identified in both branchio-oto and branchio-oto-renal syndromes.

HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_description: Impaired interactions between mouse Eyal harboring mutations found in patients with branchio-oto-renal syndrome and Six, Dach, and G proteins. J Hum Genet 47, 107-116 (2002).
HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_caption: Impaired interactions between mouse Eyal harboring mutations found in patients with branchio-oto-renal syndrome and Six, Dach, and G proteins; in addition, Defective protein-protein interactions of mutations in the EYA domain underlie brachio-oto-renal syndrome.

HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_description: Eya protein phosphatase activity regulates Six1-Dach-Eya transcriptional effects in mammalian organogenesis. Nature 426, 247-254 (2003).
HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_caption: The phosphatase function of Eya switches the function of Six1-Dach from repression to activation, causing transcriptional activation through recruitment of co-activators

HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_description: SIX1 mutations cause branchio-oto-renal syndrome by disruption of EYA1-SIX1-DNA complexes. Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A 101, 8090-8095 (2004).
HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_caption: three Six1 mutations are crucial for Eya1-Six1 interaction, and the two mutations within the homeodomain region are essential for specific Six1-DNA binding

HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_description: Six1 and Eya1 expression can reprogram adult muscle from the slow-twitch phenotype into the fast-twitch phenotype. Mol Cell Biol 24, 6253-6267 (2004).
HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_caption: Data identify Six1 and Eya1 as the first transcriptional complex that is able to reprogram adult slow-twitch oxidative fibers toward a fast-twitch glycolytic phenotype.

HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_description: Eya1 is required for the morphogenesis of mammalian thymus, parathyroid and thyroid. Development 129, 3033-3044 (2002).
HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_caption: Eya1 is required for the morphogenesis of mouse thymus, parathyroid and thyroid.

HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_description: A comparative study of Eya1 and Eya4 protein function and its implication in branchio-oto-renal syndrome and DFNA10. J Assoc Res Otolaryngol 5, 295-304 (2004).
HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_caption: constructs of the homologous region ( Eya1HR and Eya4HR) interact with Six1 prey constructs, although no interaction with Dach1 prey was demonstrable

HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_description: EYA1 mutation in a newborn female presenting with cardiofacial syndrome. Pediatr Cardiol 25, 411-413 (2004).
HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_caption: EYA1 mutation represents a previously undescribed cause of cardiofacial syndrome.

HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_description: Eya1 and Six1 are essential for early steps of sensory neurogenesis in mammalian cranial placodes. Development 131, 5561-5572 (2004).
HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_caption: During the development of epibranchial placode-derived distal cranial sensory ganglia, while the phenotype appears less severe in Six1 than in Eya1 mutants

HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_description: Functional dissection of eyes absent reveals new modes of regulation within the retinal determination gene network. Mol Cell Biol 23, 5989-5999 (2003).
HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_caption: Our data suggest that EYA requires homo- and heterotypic interactions and RAS/MAPK signaling responsiveness to ensure context-appropriate RD gene network activity.

HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_description: Independent roles of the dachshund and eyes absent genes in BMP signaling, axon pathfinding and neuronal specification. Development 131, 5837-5848 (2004).
HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_caption: dachshund and eyes absent genes have roles in BMP signaling, axon pathfinding and neuronal specification

HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_description: A role for extra macrochaetae downstream of Notch in follicle cell differentiation. Development 131, 5971-5980 (2004).
HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_caption: EMC functions downstream of Notch and upstream of EYA to regulate main body cell fate specification and differentiation

HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_description: Eya1 acts upstream of Tbx1, Neurogenin 1, NeuroD and the neurotrophins BDNF and NT-3 during inner ear development. Mech Dev 122, 625-634 (2005).
HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_caption: Eya1 signaling is critical to the normal expression patterns of Tbx1, Ngn1, and NeuroD in the developing mouse otocyst

HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_description: Eyes absent, a key repressor of polar cell fate during Drosophila oogenesis. Development 129, 5377-5388 (2002).
HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_caption: Data show that the gene eyes absent (eya) is a key repressor of polar cell fate.

HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_description: Identification of a novel mutation in the EYA1 gene in a Korean family with branchio-oto-renal (BOR) syndrome. Int J Pediatr Otorhinolaryngol 69, 1123-1128 (2005).
HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_caption: Mutations in the EYA1 gene on the chromosome band 8q13.3, have been identified to be the underlying genetic defects. We found a Korean family with BOR syndrome and identified a novel insertion mutation (c.1474_1475insC; R492PfsX40) in the EYA1 gene.

HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_description: Eya 1 acts as a critical regulator for specifying the metanephric mesenchyme. Dev Biol 284, 323-336 (2005).
HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_caption: Eya1 acts as a critical regulator for specifying the metanephric mesenchyme.

HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_description: Pax6-dependence of Six3, Eya1 and Dach1 expression during lens and nasal placode induction. Gene Expr Patterns 6, 110-118 (2005).
HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_caption: The Pax-Eya-Six-Dach network is at best only partly conserved during lens and nasal placode development.

HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_description: A somatic role for eyes absent (eya) and sine oculis (so) in Drosophila spermatocyte development. Dev Biol 258, 117-128 (2003).
HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_caption: This protein has a somatic role in spermatocyte development.

HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_description: Mechanism of hedgehog signaling during Drosophila eye development. Development 130, 3053-3062 (2003).
HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_caption: Data show that the retinal determination gene eyes absent (eya) is the crucial link between the Hedgehog signaling pathway and photoreceptor differentiation.

HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_description: Mutation of the EYA1 gene in patients with branchio-oto syndrome. Acta Otolaryngol 123, 279-282 (2003).
HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_caption: These results suggest that the S189G mutation is a candidate mutation for Branchio-Oto syndrome.

HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_description: Point mutation of an EYA1-gene splice site in a patient with oto-facio-cervical syndrome. Ann Hum Genet 70, 140-144 (2006).
HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_caption: Point mutations altering the EYA1 reading frame, can be found in patients with oto-facio-cervical syndrome.

HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_description: Patterning of the third pharyngeal pouch into thymus/parathyroid by Six and Eya1. Dev Biol 2006 Mar 9;.
HG-Commentary.HG-Commentary_caption: essential role for Eya1 and Six genes in patterning the third pouch into organ-specific primordia
